	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I kind of stumbled into playing an SK after having my lvl 17 Druid being given a Deathbringer's Rod in a trade by a passing Lvl 49 warrior.  I casually tossed off the trade as something to auction until I looked up the weapon's stats and felt my eyes bugging.  Oh yes!  It will be mine!  (dmg 30/dly 40 magic 2HB)Thus, Michelin was born (Troll).<BR>
     First off, race selection.  I chose a large race because I was building the character around the weapon.  I wanted someone who could take advantage of the weapon as early as possible so that I could survive despite the damage caps.  Large races have the option of slamming which allows them to tack on another 6-10 points of damage from level 4-12.  This slam also is a lifesaver when battling toe to toe against spellcasters; stunning them before they can get those nasty spells off.  This brought the choices down to an Ogre and Troll.  The Ogre is a good choice.  He has the highest strength and I have heard that ogres actually will have marginally better faction in the good cities than the troll.  I picked the troll, though.  I was planning on soloing a lot, at least through his early years, and the troll's regeneration makes soloing so much easier.  Less downtime and since Michelin was going to be a 'hobby' character rather than one of my main ones I really didn't want to waste a lot of time sitting around waiting to heal up.  Secondly, roleplay potential was good.  I like to have fun when I am playing, much to the chagrin of those in the zone with me, and the troll's stunted vocabulary looked like it would be endless fun.  The downside to being a troll sk is that you are the most hated person in the game.  Travel is much more severely limited than for the good races.  All of those lifesaving guards that stand at the zones are now your enemies and essentially prevent your travel from not just the good cities, but many of the outdoor zones as well.  One the flip side...I have discovered that both Freeport and Qeynos have an active underground area that is troll friendly so all is not lost.  If you like having quick access to your bank, though, you will want to think twice about a troll sk.  So far I have found three banks that will do business with me...Grobb, Oggok, and Neriak.  Be careful in Oggok though, because you are tolerated there by most but KOS to some.  For attribute points I brought Michelin's INT up to 70.  Pretty smart for the average troll, but necessary to cast the Necro spells he'll be getting later in life.  The rest of the points I dumped in STR.  Anyway, Michelin was born in Grobb (surprise surprise) and spent his first 9 seasons in Innouthule bashing frogloks.  <BR>
     Innouthule is where I realized the world of the troll sk was completely different from anything I had played in before.  The primary bad guy to beat up on in the first 5-7 levels are Frogloks.  They come in various sizes all the way from tads to foragers.  The tads and frogloks would frequently yield netted armor and by level 4 I had a complete set of netted armor.  By level 5 I was able to afford a complete set of leather armor.  A primary source of income was from selling looted netted armor to visiting PC's to the swamp.  Unlike other beginning characters you have a quest weapon almost immediately available.  Sure, it's just a rusty 2 handed sword, but that's more than most newbies start off with.  You get this by turning in four bone chips to your Guild master (same guy you turn your guild letter into for your tunic).  Do this as soon as possible and your starting damage will be in the high teens.  Once you have your sword keep collecting bone chips.  You will need them later for many of your best SK spells and it helps to have a couple of stacks available when you reach level 9.<BR>
     Two departures from the way I was used to playing.  Inn. Swamp is probably the emptiest newbie area I have ever played in which makes for great hunting and short lifespans.  Michelin died a lot.  In addition to the typical wandering creatures you find in most newbie areas there are also tons of Frogloks.  I was frequently being mobbed by 3-6 Frogloks (greens to reds).  Rather than run for the guards I just plowed on and took as many out as I could before I died.  On corpse retrieval I would frequently find my body in the middle of a circle of froggie corpses.  Always make sure to get your harm touch off before expiring.  It will take out that last Froglok or help you bring that red down to its knees before you go with it.  Also make sure you study hand to hand.  Mine went from 1 to 20 during CR's alone.  By the time your experience starts taking a hit for dying you have outpaced all but the Froglok Fishermen and Froglok Foragers and the mobbing has trickled down to 1 or 2 at a time (about 6th level or so).  After the enemies have trickled down to just a few hit that tower in the east end of the swamp.  It will have blue undead (skels mostly) and the occasional red mummy.  Camp outside the door and coax them out as they pop.  I used this strategy to level from 1-9 in 10 hours of gameplay.  Contrary to popular belief, Innouthule Swamp is a great place to level up.  Newbies are rare and passing experienced trolls frequently gave me items to make life easier.  They respect the fact that you have chosen the hard life of the Troll SK and are willing to help out.  <BR>
I hope this helps others who want to start a troll SK.  I was pretty intimidated when I first saw the &quot;EXTREME DIFFICULTY&quot; warning on the character creation page, but it hasn't been all that tough to get him to level 12.  I'd recommend it to anyone!  
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
